{"name": "encapsulation", "metadata": {"name": "encapsulation", "version": "0.2.0", "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Operating System :: OS Independent", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3"], "home_page": "https://github.com/JungeWerther/From", "license": null, "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": [], "summary": "Encapsulation and decorators made easy.", "upload_time": 1733664119}, "documentation": ["# The encapsulation library\n\nIntroducing: the `From` class.\nFor maintainable data pipelines.\n\nAdds new syntactic sugar to python!\n\n## Installation\n\n`pip install -e encapsulation`\n\n## Getting started\n\nGet started by\n\n```python\nfrom encapsulation.base import Maybe\n\nMaybe(\"a\") + \"b\" # outputs <Maybe val=(ab)>\nMaybe(None) * 2 # outputs <Nothing val=(None)>\n```\n\n_Easy to use_ decorators that elevate functions to return wrapped values instead:\n\n```python\nfrom encapsulation.base import Maybe, to\n\ndef add1(n: int):\n    return n + 1\n\n@to(Maybe)\ndef (s: int):\n    return s\n\ntest(1).bind(add1).effect(print) # prints '[2]'\n```\n\nYou can chain computations using compose(). For example\n\n```python\nfrom encapsulation.base import Just, compose\n\n@to(Just[int])\ndef add2(s: int):\n    return s\n\ncompose(Just(1), add2, add2) # equals Just(5)\n```\n"], "modules": [{"name": "encapsulation", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "encapsulation.main", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "encapsulation.adaptors", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "encapsulation.adaptors.inspect", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "v", "type": {"name": "Any", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Any", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Inspect any object."]}, {"name": "encapsulation.adaptors.good", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "val", "type": null, "de